Project Overview 
The Minorities Striving and Pursuing Higher Degrees of Success (MS PHDÆS) in Earth System Science Professional Development Program engages underrepresented minority (URM) undergraduate and graduate Earth system science student participants in a series of activities designed to:

Increase exposure to and engagement in the Earth system science community, via participation in scientific conferences, mentoring relationships, virtual activities, and fieldtrips;
Enhance professional skills, grantsmanship, oral and written communication;
Provide resources regarding future funding, education and career opportunities;
Facilitate networking opportunities with established researchers and educators;
Sustain on-going interaction, communication and support via membership within a virtual community comprised of peers, junior/senior-level researchers, and educators actively involved in facilitating full participation of minorities in the Earth system sciences. 

These activities, conducted in three phases, occur during professional society meetings, field trips, and a æcapstoneÆ event at the National Academies. As a result, URM undergraduate, graduate and recent graduate participants will be better prepared to achieve their academic and professional goals. It is also expected that because of mentor-mentee partnerships, science exposure, and networking activities, MS PHDÆS participants will remain actively engaged in their fields of specialization and respective professional societies.
Project Outcomes

The MS PHDÆS initiative has promoted the advancement of 213 URM students and recent URM doctoral degree recipients committed to achieving outstanding Earth system science careers.

Of the total 213 participants, 115 participants self-identified as African American; 47 as Puerto Rican; 27 as Hispanic/Mexican American; 13 as American Indian/Alaskan Native; 5 as Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander; and 6 as White/Caucasian, Other Hispanic, African, Asian or Multi-Ethnic. Of the 213 participants, 61% are female and 39% male. A total of 133 students began participation within MS PHDÆS as graduate students, 75 as undergraduate students, and the remaining 5 as post-baccalaureate in transition to graduate school. To date, fifty-seven (57) MS PHDÆS student participants have received their doctoral degrees. An additional 35 alumni have completed the Masters and Baccalaureate (21 and 14 respectively) as their highest degree to date and are currently employed within the STEM workforce. The remaining 121 participants are enrolled in undergraduate and graduate programs throughout the U.S. Geographic representation of participants includes 35 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and two international postdoctoral appointments &ndash; one in Saudi Arabia and the other in France.

Anonymous surveys completed annually by MS PHDÆS participants show broad agreement (96%) on the need for the MS PHDÆS as well as willingness to advocate for the program. The most cited beneficial aspects of the program fall into categories of Peer and Community Engagement, Networking, and Professional Development. At the conclusion of their MS PHDÆS experience, student participants report that they are better prepared to achieve their academic and professional goals. The following statement provides evidence of the impacts of MS PHDÆS: "The MS PHDÆs program has had a profound impact on my professional development as a geo-scientist&hellip;In academic geo-science environments, I felt acutely out of place until I ventured to my first AGU meeting with the MS PHD'S program. Once I found there were others striving to do what I had only dreamed of doing (that were from similar backgrounds), I set my goal to achieve my PhD in geology. I have been fortune enough to have won both a Ford Fellowship and an NSF graduate fellowship. These have allowed me to propose bold scientific questions as I journey towards my PhD. I feel that the MS PHDÆS program was pivotal in setting...
